\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Can you remember how many years you lived in the house where you were born?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Over fifty. 
Yes, over fifty years - we lived there. My mother - my mother and father went - to that house - when they were married, they went straight there. Yes. And then - they lived - had nine children there, and - 'course - retired like other people do. Left work
. And - we all - well we were all distributed away from home you see, some went one way and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5837119\charrsid10883825 some another}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 , and - I went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bedford{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} to live for a time. Then I went on to Croydon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Do you remember what year you went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Bedford{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Well I'd be fifteen wh
en I went to live in. When I went to live in, I went to East Lodge. It was a - he was a gentleman who kept school for - boys who - failed at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Eton{\*\xmlclose}
 and that you know. Yes. Well I went there as kitchen maid. And I stayed three years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 How many brothers an
d sisters did you have? Eight brothers and sisters apart from you was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Nine. Yes, had eight, I was the ninth you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Can you tell me about them, how they went, from top to bottom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Well, my eldest brother was a carpenter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 What was his name?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
George. And he - he married and had - family of six. Yes, and then he died and left six children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Was he a carpenter all his life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 His name was Collier, same as ours you see, my name was Collier.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Was he always a carpenter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Yes, he - he was a good carpenter, what I - you know, in those days they had to - well he was put there by - a charity that belonged to the village, and that was for boys and girls - after they - if they had behaved at school and passed they could - w
ell if their parents could afford to buy the clothes, the charity used to pay for the - putting in of them, yes. Well my brother happened to be the lucky one that year you see, and it - 'cos as I say, then he got married, well then - the sister was next t
o him. And she got married you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 How much younger was she, how many years between them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Year and nine - I think about a year and eight months. Between - now my brother was born in May and my sister was born August the tenth, twelve months August the tenth, 'cos her birthday came three days before - our three birthdays on one day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 So who was next after that sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
My brother. Very sad - my brother was - nearly just on sixteen. He was about - two - three days I think, well no, more t
han that. It must have been about a fortnight, and he was killed with an engine - on Mr Howard's - you've got that - you ought to have that, because that's ninety-five years come this November since he was killed. And I can remember it as if it was - toda
y.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Can you tell me about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Well he was - it was - he was getting ready and - for the fifth of November, 'cos we used to fifth of November in the villages is a grand day. And he said to my mother, don't let them children meddle with my things wi
ll you. And he put them in a cupboard by the fireplace, you know, old cottages always have cupboards by the fireplace, and he - she promised him she'd look after them and not let them touch them, 'cos he'd got masks and old rags, you know, trousers and th
a
t to put on and - well he was already, went off so bright to work mother said about half past five. 'Cos they used to be at work at six in the morning you see. And - he had - at nine o'clock, he was brought home dead. Yes, I mean - you wouldn't know it, w
e
ll she doesn't know it, it - we used to have ploughing machines. One plough - one engine that end, and an engine that end. And we used to have a rope in between to bring them backwards and forwards to plough, see, that was very different ploughing to what
 
it is today. Well he touched something on this engine - and it caught him there and knocked his brain out. And my mother was just downstairs with her last baby. And of course they told me at school, I was five years old. Little girl sitting by me - I reme
m
ber her so well - she said, you're brother's dead, you know how children would go. And another one this side says, don't tell her. But however when I got home - and - me brothers went - didn't go to our school, they went Paynden school, my father wouldn't
 
let them go where there was a woman. Used to - no, he used to say that they needed - a master. So my - they had to walk four mile each way to school. All my brothers had to go. Yes. And pay for it. Mother used to - mother used to say sometimes, I don't kn
o
w where I'm going to find that money for Monday morning. There was me brother Marry and Sid and Frank, all three wanted fourpence each. I wanted a penny. Oh that's my - my - then my next brother, he died you see, he - he was vaccinated and he was vaccinat
e
d, it must have been a very bad - family, and it all came out all over him, and my father kicked up an awful bother about it and he said, if ever - they attempted - to vaccinate his children from another child what he'd do with them, but however - they ma
naged to get calf limp after that. But the - the child died. Frank, yes, he died.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 They managed to get what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
No, calves lymph. Lymph. It was called. It was what - the real stuff you see, and of course I think they use it now and then they - put i
t away - and keep it. It's a very - you can't get it very often because they have to get it from freshly calved - you see, when the cows calve they have to get it then. Well, then he died you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Was there about two years between each one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Well, mostly a year and eight months or a year and - somewhere like that.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 That's number four, who came after him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
My brother Charlie had croup very badly and he choked. Yes. So - there you can see the brothers come along. Then my brother Harry -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 You had three brothers died then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Yes. Younger. Yes. Then - how many have you got down?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Five I've got down.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Well then there's only me brother Frank to go down. I had six. Yes, I had George. George and - Sibley. Sibley, Sibley and Charlie
. No, wait a minute, Charlie, yes, Charlie comes after - Frank had - I've got Frank but I can't - have you got Frank down? Yes. Frank, yes. No, it was only George that - died and left any children. The others hadn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 So Sibley, Charlie and Frank all died when they were children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
No, it was George left the six children, but the others hadn't married then. Or if they married they were away from home, they'd gone from home you see. 'Cos my sister, she'd gone and got - she'd got two children but - she was away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Who came after Frank?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Then my brother Harry, he - you haven't got Harry down? No, well he went to live in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Dorset{\*\xmlclose}. So of course he didn't come home - very often.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 What did he do for a living?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 He was a soldier, he went out to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}India{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} for seven years. Then when he come home he married and settled in Dorset.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 What did he do, do you know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Oh he - he was with horses, always with horses. Because he was in the - Artillery in the Army you see. He was - in the Royal Artillery
 and he was always with horses. - And he said he couldn't leave horses. Yes. Well that's Harry, well then - there's only Frank. And he went to - he went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}, he was a stonemasoner. And do you - I don't know if you know that big building - it's {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Canada{\*\xmlclose} - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
country-region}}Canada{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - right on the top. Big - big stone building, yes, well he worked on that and caught Sunstroke. He died - he went home - he went home to his lodgings. It was the first of September. I was in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Scotland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, I - I was. I couldn't get home. And - they br
ought him home, he - but he - he - carried on during the day as well as he could but he went home in the - during the night he passed away. Yes. You know, sunstroke is bad if you get it bad. Yes. And - then there was my sister Lily, she had German measles
. And she had - I had measles three times. Yes. I always had measles if everybody had them. Mum'd say, she'll have 'em. Yes, I had them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 So Lily had German measles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Yes. I am now with measles. No, but that - I mean that carries our family - they scattered you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 What happened to Lily?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Oh she - she was between eight and nine I think, wait a minute I'll you - November. She'd be nine in November. We lost nine of the same age in our village with measles, German measles, and the vicar - vi
car's wife as well. We had nine young girls - little - well they were just growing nice. She was getting what my mother called useful. When us others had gone away you see she'd run an errand. And - they was stricken down, one woman, she lost - one - Mrs 
Riseley, she lost her - the first one, and while she'd gone to bury that one another one died. We had some tragic things happen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 They didn't have the medicines in those days did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 No, but of course that was nothing to do with - that. But that
 was the family, how we were scattered out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Where did you come?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Well I come you see - on the seventh, I'm the seventh. Seven - seventh born.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Who came after you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 I was seventh born.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Who came after you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Charlie - with croup. And - and Lily.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 I should have one more I think, Sarah?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Well you - you can't have, you've got George and Sid and Harry. Three - another baby died when the mother - she went to bed with - oh Sally. Have you - have you got Sally?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Where did she come?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Well, she - she was away - she used to be lace making. She was a lace maker. She -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Was she older or younger than you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Oh, older than me, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Who was she next to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Well I've got to think where the boys come in. No, she - 
you've got her some - you've got Sarah. Are you sure? Well she was a lacemaker, she had to earn her living by lacemaking. Yes, she had to go to lacemaking school. Parents - Mrs - Mrs Pickering's school - at - at Platham, and she kept a school. And they le
arned - A.B.C. there while they were working. Lacemaking. Oh she made some beautiful lace. My mother made lace for Queen {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname State}}Victoria{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Yes, and it was as wide as that. And it was all colours. Green, I used - I used to have to take it in to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Bedford{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} to a lacemake
rs, I had a - I had some runnings - and it used to have beads on it. Beads were worked in it. Not - not down the side there, but in - on there you see, on the - yes. And - and blue, green and blue and red. I don't remember any other colour. But her and ou
r next door neighbour made it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 When did they have time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Oh had to have time, well you made time when you made lace.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 With all those children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Well you got up in the morning and done the work what they did and - put the pot on. We didn't
 get - two or three saucepans like this, we had a big pot you know. You've seen them I expect. With two handles. Yes. Well they used to put that - right over the fire, and we used to cook everything in it. We used to put the potatoes in that and used to p
ut the cabbage in that so that you could left them straight out you see. And - yes, and then we had boiled puddings, we didn't have many baked puddings R" can tell you. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 You'd start that early in the morning would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Oh yes. Well - mother
, as soon as she got us off to school when we were young she used to put her - made out, and a pillow from out and you'd see them clicking away for life. Until about twelve and then the children coming out of school, they'd have to - oh I must see about d
i
nner. Well they got nothing to do, only take all these up you see. They were all ready and all cooked. 'Cos they used to get up and put them in - at the time. Meals were so different, you had the flavour of everything. I mean, you had all flavours and yet
 
you had one - one flavour if you can reckon that. Well that's how we had to live. And the mothers used to do that. And there used to be lace buyers come round, and buy it. And - it depended on how nice you did and how clean you kept it. Yes. If - if it wa
s the - all - at all discoloured in any way they wouldn't buy it. Then you'd got to sell it somewhere else, privately wherever you could. Yes. They don't - I think that's made - some of them make it at Flitchit don't they. I believe so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Where did your mother learn to make it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
At Bownest. At - her mother - her mother and everybody before her made it. Yes. My grandmother was making lace when she was eighty-four. And she was making for a Captain Browning's wife who - who was having a - baby, she was 
having - you know that - lace - like that for - what's it called - what do I say sometime, that's so and so lace? Oh dear, what's it - well anyway - it's only a little tiny lace like that. It's fro trimming baby's things, and she wanted two dozen yards of
 that, and my grandmother said to her, I don't think I shall be able to - finish it. She said, oh you will. She did, and some more beside. Yes. Oh everybody made lace. We had nothing else. I mean, you -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 How much money would you get for it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 It dep
ended on your work. My grandmother had - any - anybody'd give her more - than - you know what - really what she charged - than what they would some people. Because she was a good - what she called a good old hand at it. But you - I don't think anybody who
 
didn't see it - would know - what a pillow is like unless they saw it dressed or undressed. Like you have - bobbin - pockets here, and you have your parchment coming up from there. Over there like that. Well that parchment's got to be pricked. See? For th
e
 pattern. Well then you have to have another thick cover to come up over that to keep that clean, and you've got to have another cover what we call - coming along here, where you put your bobbins in there - there. Then you've got to have another one - to 
put over - and the bobbin - and then there's the bobbin wheel. That - that -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Very complicated?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Oh - you've no idea, no, I don't think anybody - she did try to learn didn't you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Were they quick at it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Oh yes. Oh my mother's - bobbins w
ould go - and I used to say, let me have - do that, go on, I'll do that for - you - don't you touch it, she'd say, you'll spoil my work. No. And we used to have - what we call - now what we call them pins - used to get - have special pins for it. Oh dear,
 
I've forgot these things in my head. Yes. We used to have some pin - big pins which we pinned the corners down of the covers and they used to be called gluckens pins. Gawkins pins. These pins that we used to use here was real lace pins. Well then - we use
d
 to have to buy the thread - and we have to buy that - called that in slips, we didn't buy thread like you buy today. We call - what they call - number one slip, number four slip, number eight slip. We could only work them three on those pillows. And - th
e
y were - sort of - like wool is tied up sometimes you know. As if it - they were slips. And you put that on your bobbin, on your wheel and then you had to - well you got a lot of fixtures like this. And you have to hold your bobbin in like this while you'
re turning wheel.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Did it take you long to learn?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
No. I could - you know really I mean, it - if you talk about lace work, it really is interesting if you could see the things - that - to work with. Now, I saw a - in the paper the other day, no, it
 was in a book - and - it was a thing about like that, and they'd been trying to find out what it was, and nobody could tell what it was. But somehow or other they had got somebody belonging - as knew lace, and that was a - now then - not a bobbin. You sa
w
 it, I've shown it you, a bobbin hold - not the bobbin - well it was belonging to lace, what you put - what you use - for a bobbin, and it was really - it was worth a lot of money. I think it - I'm not sure if we - we haven't put it away. If I do find it 
I'll send it to you, it was called a - it was a -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Could you make lace now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Not myself, no, my mother used to say I was too round in the bottom part. I can - no, I had too much running about to do. Yes. Well I had those - all those brothers to run
 about for you know, and had all the errands. And then I had to go to school. I - I went to school at three you know. And I left at ten, I never went a day after I was ten. I had -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 What did you do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 I happened to pass - when I was ten and of cour
se I left school that day and - I said to my mother - am I going to school any more? She said, no, I can find you a job. And then - then I had to - I did have a job too. I had to help. My grandmother was living with us you see. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 All in one cottage?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 How did you sleep?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Well - one - one of the boys slept }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5837119\charrsid10883825 downstairs}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
. And - my sister had gone out - she'd gone to service you see, so she was away, that was two of 'em away. One we lost, that was three. And I had to sleep where I coul
d. I had to creep in with some of 'em. No, my - my sister Lily and I had a small bed, up that way - like up that corner of the cottage. They were fairly big rooms you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 How many bedrooms did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Only two. That's what I say, one had to sleep downstairs. Then he slept -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Where did grandmother sleep?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
She had the back room upstairs to herself. Oh I slept with her - to - for a time, and then somebody said to mother - I don't think it's good for your girl to sleep with your mother. 
So mother, said, well she's always slept with her more or less, and if - until - if mother isn't well - of course mother - she used to be away sometimes for the other children, and - she said - it - the - your mother takes the goodness out of my - out of 
me. Now I never could see that. They - they said that it - as she breathed so she took my breath - a young breath, and that used to make me look so pale. 'Cos I was very very pale when - yes. Well I was so fair like - you know. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Were you strong when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Well I had to be.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Tell me what you used to do, the errands you used to run?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
What, after I left school? Well I'm afraid I done a lot for old people. Who got two - very old people next door, Mr and Mrs Poole. They were b
oth very old and they'd kept a public house at Pevenham, before they retired and come - and they lived next door and they'd got one daughter - not married. Well then she had to work at that lace - and help to keep 'em. All what's to come in was two shilli
n
gs a week, that was a shilling for the mother - mother and shilling for the father. And the rent was two and tuppence. So where had they got to live. Well - her name was Harriet, and Harriet used to say to me, now Polly, will you clean my floor - and my k
i
tchen, will you scrub my front for me while I'm gone to Bedford to do a bit of shopping and take my lace? I've got to sell me lace before I can do my shopping. So I shall be quite a time. Well I used to - scrub her front, 'cos we were all bricks then, the
r
e weren't no carpets. I used to scrub her front first, the - they was fronts as led up to the front door, and gates you see. Well then I scrubbed her kitchen for her, I used to say to the old lady, you go down the garden while I scrub the kitchen - I don'
t
 want to be moved, she'd say. And the old man, I used to say, you go in the barn. And he used to say, don't you be so saucy. Well then - when she come home all she'd got to do was to dust. Well then - Mrs Armstrong - was not a very - well I don't know wha
t - I wouldn't know what to say about her. I used to do all her errands. And I used to -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Did she live next door?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Yes. No, she didn't live - she lived at number five, with the pump house.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 What was the pump house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Haven't you - the pump
 house? Well it - it was the pump for all the whole row. You see, and she lived at that house and we called it the pump house. Well she had gangrene, and she was very ill, she went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
City}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and she died. And of course - mother had - being very friendly
 my mother was always - ready to help anybody, you know, and she, you know, if there was any confinements, she - always - they'd always come and knock her up in the night. That was my mother. Yes, they missed my mother when she went. They all did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Did you get paid for these little jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
I used to get about - perhaps I had a penny, perhaps I had tuppence - might - if I was very very big I got tuppence. Most ever I had was tuppence.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 What did you do with it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Saved it for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5837119\charrsid10883825 Clapham}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825  Feast, an
d that was yesterday. That's funny you should come - yes, I was - Clapham all day Sunday I was the Clapham Feast. And I - I - perhaps I had only fourpence - fivepence it might be, fivepence I'd got at the feast. And I'd got to buy everybody something.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 What was the feast like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Oh - grand, it was a grand day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 What happened?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Well it was an open day - if you went to Clapham now and could find any one of the old people they'd tell you. It was an open day - open house for everybody. Everybod
y was welcome to come in and help themselves. And we always had - we - I bought it with me didn't I. Yorkshire pudding tin like that. And we - everybody used to go to the bakehouse and - that day, all - you want some Yorkshire pudding, and - they used to 
charge - used to charge us more that day than they did other days. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 How much?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Well we only paid tuppence other Sundays but - Clapham, when it was the feast they'd charge you according to what joint you'd got. You see? 'Cos the heat. If it wa
s a small joint they kept that back and put that in the last. If it was a leg - which many didn't have - more like half a cows head was - no, we - they - Mrs - Pettit used to say - we have some very funny joints come in don't we.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 What else happened on the feast day? Where did you spend your money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Well - we used to have some stalls. Oh yes, and - we used to have dancing. And we had a band. And - oh we had real good - it was a holiday, a real holiday. And used to get some - well - I don't know, yo
u wouldn't see them now. Little round cakes like that, pink, with - powder all over them. You know - you - you remember them. And - then we used to get nuts, there used to be nuts and - rock. And then used to have one of them - you know - if it stopped th
e
re - that was all right, you got that bit, but you didn't very often get it. And - this Mr Ogden was a - old man, he was a chapel man. And he used to do this - he used to go to feasts, well he'd get these feasts ready on a Sunday and be ready to go out fo
r Monday, and he'd perhaps Sunday he'd be working all that, and then go to chapel at night and pray. And he'd say - in between - hallelujah you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Was he the baker?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
No, he was the man that did - he got a donkey cart and he used to go out with t
hese to these feasts. Every - he knew the feasts, all the feasts round. Well he used to go out with these. But what used to amuse us was, he was getting ready all day - getting his things ready to go out next day, and then at night he'd go to chapel. And 
-
 oh we had some fun in our days, though - that's what I say, these young people they don't - well, we had to make our fun then. We really had to make it. We had nothing. I can remember the games we used to play you know, many times, yes. Actually what I d
id, well that's what - how I used to spend - had to spend - then I helped mother with the washing. Yes, in - there were other things, often I had to run in to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Bedford
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - to take a message for the doctor to come 'cos see we'd no doctor near. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 How far was it to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Bedford{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Well it's two mile to get into - to get to Bedford, and then you've got to get - it was two and a half mile to three - for us to get in. I mean - we - by the time I'd run six mile - I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 You were saying you went to this policeman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Yes, I went to this policeman and helped her out with her twins. Used to take twins out you see, well that left her with only the baby. She could get on. And - mother said - after I'd been with them some time she said, well now, I think it's ti
me you began to think about a job properly, you see. And - I happened to look in the paper one night, and I said, oh here's a job going down {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Cardigan Road{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}. And of course I knew {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Cardington Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} so well. So she - I said, I think I'll apply for it. She said, 
you'll never get it. She said, they'll say you're too little. 'Cos I wasn't very - I'm not - well - well I mean I'm - I'm really short, not - too short - anyway, she said, you'll never reach - the things you know, she thought about me having to reach up }
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5837119\charrsid10883825 high}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
. Anyway I went. I can remember it as well as anything I went in on the second of November. And - they'd been hunting all day, they hadn't come in, the lady and gentleman, and - anyway - the - maid, one of the parlourmaids it was, she put me in the study
 and she said, if you sit - wait a little while I think they won't be long before they're in, because they like to get home before it gets too dark. Well I sat there and I thought it seemed ages. But however - when Mrs Trevor come in, she came straight to
 
the study where I was, and - she said, good evening. She was all in her hunting clothes you see, and she got a - hung - habit over her arm. I can see her now standing there looking at me as much as to say, you don't look as if you can do much. And - she s
a
id, what can you do? And of course, you know, the conversation went on and I said - I haven't been out really not living out before. So she said - shall you mind? So I said, well I don't think so. And she said, could you come to me quick, 'cos my maid wen
t - wants to get away. Her mother had got a shop - and she was ill and she wanted to get home to look after it. And - I went in, I tell you I stayed three years.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 You were happy there were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 And that - they're all died and the son - he was - h
e was - Sir George Barry weren't he.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 What did you do there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Well then I left there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 What did you do there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Oh I was kitchen maid, had to work - I had to be down at five in the morning.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 What else did you do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Well - well I ha
d to be down at five and I had a stove - a - coming from that end of the house to hear and I had all that to black lead and light the fire and get the kitchen all nice and clean, all the fireplace and that had to white - all white. I can tell you, by six 
o
'clock one of the men used to come in. How you getting on? I'd say, all right. He'd say, you want to go and open them gates. I said, that's not my job. He says, well, is there a cup of tea going? That's what he used to come in for. I'd say, well there wil
l be in a minute or two. And he'd come back again and - and have a cup of tea. Well then at seven o'clock breakfast for all of us in the kitchen. And then -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 How many were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 There were six - seven - seven of us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Was it a big house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Oh yes. Well we had - I had - I can't think now just think how many there were. I think - it was - I think it was eight young gentlemen, and the Captain, and Mr and Mrs Trevor and the two children and nanny and all us servants. I had all that to wash up 
and cook - and get ready for. There was a housekeeper - yes. Mrs - now then - oh - do you know I've forgotten her name. Her name was Sarah but - we didn't call her Sarah. Sarah Gammons. Gammons. She come from Highsham. A little tiny village - a very very 
t
iny village it is - out Owley way. Yes. It's like a little hamlet. Well she - that's where she came from. Well then - you see we had late dinner - well there was - breakfast was got over. Well then - of course everybody went to their work. And the - parlo
u
rmaid went to hers, the housemaid - she went upstairs to hers. And - Goodman, I told you the wrong name. Sarah Goodman. From - from Highsham. Good job - you haven't got it down have you? Well it won't matter will it. Well - yes. Well, then - they all went
 
- we all went to our work and get - and we got on, all the men had gone out and gone down. And then - we had - a few minutes rest. And we had a cup of tea perhaps and perhaps we didn't - - depended what time we got. We had to begin to prepare for dinner. 
W
e got all the vegetables to get ready. And - I had all the plates - to make sure that they were all clean and put up on the racks. Vegetable dishes, and the silver dishes for the sweets. It is - I had hard work there but I did like - I used to like it. An
d -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Were they nice people to work for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Well I didn't see much of them. No. While - Mrs - Trevor used to come out and give her orders to Mrs Goodman, and I used to be busy perhaps somewhere else doing something you see. Perhaps I was cleaning the 
back stairs down. Might be that or - anything to get away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Were did you sleep?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Oh we had a lovely - we - four - four of us slept in one big room. One - one - one up there, and one up here and one there and one there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 At the top was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Right at - I don't know - well, no, the young gentlemen had - they slept that way, we didn't have any connection with them at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Who were the young gentlemen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Well - I - Mr Oakley was one - from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, he used to live in Eccleston Square.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 What did he do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Well he, was training because he failed at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}Eton{\*\xmlclose}. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 This was the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 These - these young gentlemen - they'd been at Eaton and 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Harrow{\*\xmlclose} and they failed. And you see, one was trained - one - wanted - perhaps for 
the clergy, one for the sailor, one for - they had - they had - whatever they were training for they failed. Well they come there to pass on and they had a Captain and Mr Trevor, he used to teach them you see. There was about - nineteen. Going twenty. Oh 
yes. Oh they were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5837119\charrsid10883825 top hats}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
. They were very smart - oh they were very smart people. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Who was the Captain, what did the Captain do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
The Captain? Well he trained the ones that wanted to go to sea. You see, the Navy - he came from the Navy. But h
e had a cottage on his own, next door, the cottage belonged to the house. Where the coachman I think used to live. But Cecil Rhodes had one room, Cecil Rhodes was there. Yes. And I remember that. Yes, and he was - he was - he failed, and so he was there, 
yes, he was there, he was a very nice fellow too, I used to like him. Well - I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Did he speak to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
I got very fed up with it because I mean - I got so tired of a night you know. You know, and never got a holiday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Not at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 No, I had no holiday. They used to say - Sundays was our holidays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Did you have Sunday off?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Oh no. Only from two o'clock 'til six. Then I used to trot home. I don't know why I went home. Well I - I don't really know, I mean - I walked all that way for 
nothing, there was - because I should have been - I saw her on the Saturday. Yes. Mother often popped in on Saturday dinner time, when she was in shopping. And - she'd say, shall - you be home tomorrow? I'd say, maybe, and I may not, don't know. If the we
ather was bad I didn't go. But otherwise I want. And that finished it. When I left there. I left in August and I went in November, so I had just two months in between for the three years. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Tell me some more about the young gentlemen, how long did they stay there?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Well until they could pass. 'Til they - they'd go away you see, they'd go away to - to pass. And then you see if they did pass they'd finished then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 That was for university was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 We didn't see any more of them, but he us
ed to have another one come in their place. He was always got somebody waiting to come in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Did you get to know them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Well - yes, some of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Did they speak to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Yes. Some of them was very nice and some of them was - Mr Alexander,
 he was a - well, one of them you know. Now Mr Walker - I really liked him very much, he always used a - got a nice word for you. Then there was Mr Oakley, but I don't think he was one of these Oakley's, I don't think he was one of them. Then there was Mr
 Chalmers, he was an Irish - he was Irish. And then we had another one from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Scotland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. We - some very nice boys they were. But they never interfered. They never was allowed to come near the place, where - the house. They had their own quarters you see. And now -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 When was this, how old were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
I was trying this morning to think what year it was. Now it must have been - about twenty - when I'd be twenty-one. I was twenty-one when I was with - Mr Blades. And he was the Mayor of Bedrod then. And whil
e I was with them they had to change their name. They had a lot of money and property left them, but they couldn't take it over unless they changed their name. And they had to change their name.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Tell me about the murder, what murderer was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 We
ll it - it was a young girl and a young fellow. It was this - it was his cousin. And he - he wanted her badly and she wouldn't have anything to do with him, and he went one night to - to call there, and he went to the front door. And as she opened the fro
nt door to him, you know, he shot her straight away dead.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 What did the Mayor have to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Well he was to be present.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 At the hanging?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
He has to be present with so many councilors you see. Of course I don't know what they do today 'cos I'm not interested in it, but I was interested in that because I was there and had to be - in it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 You said on the day you took him a cup of tea, on the day of the hanging?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Oh on the day of the hanging, oh that was a dreadful day. And he was - he 
- we never saw - I never - we never saw daylight that day. He was - a day seemed fitted for the thing you know. I shall never forget -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Was the man upset, was Mr Blade upset?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Yes, because he wasn't well at the time. He'd had a heart - attack, he'
d been worried over this money and - property you know. He'd got twelve children. And I was cook for 'em.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 You were cook then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Yes. I went, you see, from - I went from me kitchen maid to cook. Yes. Well, more money you see, I - I mean more money.
 No, but it was very hard work. Because I had the - kitchen breakfast there, and I had a dining room, and I had the - thingy now - nursery. There was two nurses, and two children up there. And then - let me see, we had - I can't - I can't - applied for th
e job you see. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Why did you leave the other one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Now let me tell you, I was in domestic service. Well you see, I began down below, as a kitchen maid. Well then you see, I kept going to better - places, and more money. And each place I went t
o I got more money. Well you see, there was a tremendous family with this - he'd got twelve children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 He was the Mayor of Bedford?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Yes. And - they were all at home, none of 'em at school - away at school, they were all - more or less of them wer
e going to the high school, which is high school now. And of course - I couldn't tell you but that - my father was all in with that - with that school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 What did your father do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 No. Oh my father was a man - he could do anything. But he was a fore
ster really. He liked - that work, he liked studying trees. But I mean, anything - that he wanted to do he could do. He was - well, with a family you've got to haven't you. It's like this one, the Blades. And they - I told you, they had to take - name of 
T
urner, to get the money and the property, and the land and all that that come into it. There was a whole - estate to come. And unless they took that - that name - they couldn't get it. So that was all done while I was there. And - I think - now, the lady 
that the - the lady that the money - was left - you know, left it, she lived over Eatonsoshan way. Yes. But anyway they got the money and the children and - were all educated after that. And - they all went - farther a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5837119\charrsid10883825  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 field. Well I left there after that trial of the murder. I used - I used to feel -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 How long were you there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Oh they kept a good - a good staff of servants. They had a good staff. And - there he was very kind to me, the man was. When I left him - left - it was - left the house on Ch
ristmas Eve, he gave me a bottle of wine, port wine, and he hoped that would pick me up. And he said, if it does you any good come back and I'll give you another one. You don't get that today do you. Well I - he did, he gave me that. But I got on well and
 then of course I went to - I've got to think where I went to next. Oh I went to Lansdowne House. Sixty-five young ladies. Boarding school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Was that in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Bedford{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 It was in - that was in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Lansdowne Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - not {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Lansdowne Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} but it was Lansdowne House in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Linden Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. See, it's funny but it was - the back - the back of the house stood in - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Lansdowne Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, and all the front was in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Linden Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. So it was - Lansdowne - we used to laugh about it. Well, I went from there -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Were you a cook there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Cook. Yes, I got six under me. Yes. YES.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Was it hard work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
I kept getting up you see, getting more money. And then I wanted to get away. And my mother didn't want me to go away from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Bedford{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 but however I - I made up me mind, then I went to Croydon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 How old were you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 I went - right away you - see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 How old were you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Oh I went - from one place to the other.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 How old were you when you went to Croydon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Oh - I - I was twenty-one when I was with the Mayor. And I
 was twenty-two - nearly twenty-three when I went to Croydon. Then I went to Croydon, and I went to a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5837119\charrsid10883825 newly married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825  couple. And there weren't enough work. There was only two maids, but they gave good wages. And that was everything you see. They give good wages, I got a rise of four pound.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Were you a cook again?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Then of course I thought I was very big. I'd got a friend in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Brighton{\*\xmlclose}. And - she wrote and said what wonderful - things were going on down their way, why didn't I come. So of course I gave in me notice and - went off to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
Brighton{\*\xmlclose} and stayed there seven years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Where were you in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Brighton{\*\xmlclose}
?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Well in - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Brighton{\*\xmlclose}
 we were in - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Poundmere Avenue{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} first. Do you know it? Well then I - we moved from there, we had - they had - furnished places, 
they took the house you see, gentlemen used to take a house. Well that's - I was with him and I used to go to Scotland.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 What family was this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
They were Jews. But they were very good people, I stayed with them - well until I left {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Brighton{\*\xmlclose}. Then I come back to Brighton - from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Brighton{\*\xmlclose}
. I wasn't very well. I'd lost three brothers. You see. During - it was during the war. And I was older in the first world war - war like - before the war you know this was. This was when South African war was going on. I was in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Brighton{\*\xmlclose} when the South African men come home, marched home. YES.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Can you remember it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Oh remember those - I remember the war before that. And there was such a lot of people that had lost eleven in that South African war. Cousins you 
know and one and the other. And - well then I - came back from - he said - I went to see a doctor - and he - used to live in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Bedford{\*\xmlclose} but he bought a practice in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
Brighton{\*\xmlclose} in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Selwood Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And I went to see him because I knew him, and he said, Brighton's get
ting too much for you, you'll be much better if you went back inland. He said, it's too strong for you. I don't know why, but I had to work very hard. And I was right down in the area. You know, where you had to go down - and I - see I had to live by gas 
- gaslight, you couldn't see down there to do anything. And I - I think it got me - you know, down a bit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Was it long hours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Long hours. Oh yes, very long hours. Sometimes - I didn't have - so bad, it wasn't so bad all the years, sometimes when they went away we had it a bit easier - then, but - anyway soon after that we were - we - I can't -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Can you tell me about when you went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Scotland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Oh well, we used - they used to travel one day and us - we }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5837119\charrsid10883825 travelled}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825  another. They'd go
 the day before - and they'd stay at the - Great Northern Hotel at Kings Cross. They used to stay there for the night. Well we - would clear up what there was to clear up. Three of us went. Jane and I and Cleo. And - we used to to go the next day and then
 we used to stay at Great Northern Hotel and have a meal there and go off from Kings Cross nine o'clock at night, travel all night. Yes, well we used to get to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Perth{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} - about five in the morning. Cold, miserable, feel it - oh, I can feel it now. Five o'clock
 in the morning, nobody about you see. And we were waiting for a train then on - to go to - Avimore. And we had to change at Avimore. And - then we went on again, we had to pick up another train. And I'd got all the luggage - for all of them, five - five 
o
f them and three of us. And I'd got five bicycles. Yes. And I lost one bicycle at Avimore and I shall never forget this now. I ran down the platform after the train and I said, you've a bicycle belonging to me. And he said, well stop there. He wouldn't st
o
p the train of course. And I kept going on with it. And he said, it'll come later. I did manage hear that. It'll come later. And I went back to the others and we got our luggage all on and got everything but this bicycle. Well then when we got down to Gra
n
down, we got there. That was about - I think about - I think it was about ten in the morning. And I said, oh what I'd give for a cup of tea. And luckily they had - they had made the tea ready for us, they saw us coming up the road so - never mind that we 
w
ere - they took a house there you see. It was called Delcusha, a queer name, I don't know what made it have - have a name like that. And anyway - we - used to stay until September - then October began to get those dreadful - mists, you know, and they used
 to say, well we'll soon pack up and go back - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Brighton{\*\xmlclose}
. And used to be very good time, they used to go out and catch fish, lovely salmon, and shrimps. Oh they used to bring them in and I'd cook them alive. I had to.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Did they go shooting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 They'r
e only white when you see them you know and when they come out they're all lovely pink. I know people don't think ever shrimps was white like that. Just like baby - flesh they are. Well anyway - we - after that I got back I didn't stop - settle down, I te
l
l you I didn't feel well, so I went to this doctor and - and - he said, I think if you went back to your own natural - nature - in the country, he said, you'd be all right. Well I was twenty-seven then. I began to think that I was on a shelf and all sorts
 of things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Did you have boyfriends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Well then I - I happened to see a place - in the paper advertised in the country at Ravendon, whether you know - so I applied for it. And I - yes, she said, well - she wrote. 'Course there weren't the telephon
e like there is now. Not in those days. And - she wrote and - this lady did and she said, meet me at the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Midland{\*\xmlclose}
 station, such a day and such a day and I went. And - I always - I always remember - we wore veils then. Of course you wouldn't - know all this.
 But I know I had a veil on. And she looked at me as she come in the station as much as to say - a cook - with a veil on? And she said, lift that veil. See I think she - thought I'd got something to hide you know. And anyway when - I had the job - I got t
he job and I stayed two years and I - then I was married you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 How did you meet your husband?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Well I met him - we'd been to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Woburn
{\*\xmlclose}, you know {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Woburn{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} don't you? Well we'd been to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Woburn
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} church. And we were coming home, one of the maids and me, 
we were coming home and he came over - on - on his beat, 'cos he was a gamekeeper you see, and he was on his - beat, and I said to her as we were coming back - 'cos we had to be back at - nine o'clock if we wanted any supper. If we didn't get back - we di
d
n't get any supper. You see, it was all put away and - locked up. And I said to her, who's this fellow coming along? So she said, oh that's the knew 'keeper. So I said, do you speak to him? She said, no. Oh no. I said, well I'm going to. Yes. She said, yo
u
 would. And she was a great tall girl, Julia. Ever such a big - well she - well she was a big person altogether, she was parlourmaid. And she said, you daren't. I said, oh daren't I? So I said, good evening, to him. And he stopped you see. And we had a ch
at. And he said, it's {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Salford{\*\xmlclose} police. So - we said, well we didn't know Salford, we didn't go to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Salford{\*\xmlclose}
. So he said, oh will you go tomorrow? Oh, we said, no, we wouldn't go to Salford Feast, we didn't know what it was like. And - anyway - he said, well - 
you'll get some rock anyway. And - we never heard anymore, we never thought anymore about it. But well - he sent me some rock. His brother, Barry's brother, because his brother was - under-gardener there, and - he came the next morning, he said - Alf sent
 you this. I said, what is it? He said, I don't know. He was a bit shy. I opened it and there }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5837119\charrsid10883825 was}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825  - some really feast rock, and it's different - any rock you get, not like that rock you get from the - beach. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 What's it like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 It's gypsies rock.
 Yes. It's Gipsy Smith used to make it, and he used - they used to have it and make it like that, pull it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Was it coloured?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
You could have coloured if you wanted, you could have pink or you could have brown, but the brown was the nicest. YES? TH
EN they used to cut a lump off and - roll it up. Make it in the - and that's how it came about you see, well then I stayed there you see for two years. And then my mother had a very bad heart attack, and she couldn't do anything, so I went home. I was hom
e
 six weeks and then - we decided during that six weeks to be married at Easter. And - Easter. Well I couldn't get married at Christmas because - I'd been - I don't know what - I'd hurt that knee something, I don't know what I done, and - she - he insisted
 
on having the doctor. And he was a very - well he was an old - good old doctor he was, a real good old doctor, one of the old fashioned ones. He come in and he'd say - have you got a cup of tea girl? And he'd stand back to his - the fireplace. And drink i
t
. And - would perhaps forget to say, how are you? He'd be gone. Wouldn't he? Another time he'd sit down and have a chat if you wasn't too busy. But anyway, we - we got settled down and then I went from one lodge to another lodge. This - house where I live
d with these people, Yarboroughs - they were - they were very nice people and they'd got four daughters, and they were all ready to come out, you know. Eighteen. The eldest one, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Nancy{\*\xmlclose}, she got married in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And - the other - the - second one she married at Weve}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5837119\charrsid10883825 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
don, and the third one, she married - Lord Attarcliffe's - I don't know - don't know the family do you, they're down in - they're {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Lancashire{\*\xmlclose}
 family. And then the youngest one, she married a brewer - brewery gentleman, Bevan. And he - they all did well, and they - they used to all visit me. YES? After - yes, they all used to visit me after I was married.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 You lived in a lodge house did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Yes. That was called Wavendon Lodge where I lived with them. Then I went to the 'keepers lodge. We
ll that was about - quarter of a mile weren't it, I should think, not more, about a quarter of a mile away, just down a hill, that's all it was. But I was away from them, I used to see them so often. YES? AND when - when she was coming along - she made me
 my first long gown. And she -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Who did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
The lady. She said, I'm making one for my daughter and I'm making one exactly like it for you. Yes. Yes, well I - I was with them, I went back - to them - after I was married, times I went back and helped o
ut. When the girls got married I always went and helped out. And when Mrs Yarnborough died, I went and helped out then. Then Mr Yarnborough died - he didn't die, he went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}
London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - in - I think it was in Kensington Gore he went - to live, he had a flat there. And he didn't like it, and his daughter was living at - where the - horses are always running.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5979360\charrsid10883825 {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}As}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 cot{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 No. Oh dear. Well you know where the - where the races -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Where did you go after the Yarboroughs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Well you see, I - I was in me own home then, I was in the lodge.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 What happened to the estate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Well it - eventually after - I lived there forty years. Yes. And then you see the estate was broke up, he died - gentleman belonged to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Who came after the Yarboroughs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Wh
o came with the Yarboroughs? Yes, that was after - after the Yarboroughs. Then you see - we went on with our work as usual, things kept happening and - you know - on the place, different - servants kept coming in and leaving and going and you know all tha
t
 sort of thing. We kept on - we - well we had - well we - you - how old were you - you were twenty-three weren't - no, how old were you when we left the lodge? You forget don't you? Well the gentleman died. And I'm afraid - he was a millionaire when he ca
me over - from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}America{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. He bought a ship load of - paid for a ship to come over and bring - and then he got mixed up with a lot - during the war. And he drank himself to death. Yes. Well then, after that - the - the lady - I never did call her Lady. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Why?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Well she didn't behave like a lady.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 How did she behave?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Well - I couldn't say what reason but - it - you see, you know what it is when it's a double family don't you, there was - his family and her family and then another young family. And she treated these elder boys dreadful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Were they American?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Yes, yes. No, no, his - his two boys - he lost the daughter, and these two boys, they were - growing up and they needed treatment, they needed proper - she used to slight them in every way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Was she English?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 She - oh yes, her father was a clergyman. Yes. At 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Kew{\*\xmlclose}. He didn't come from there, but - she was - she was absolutely mad on cars. She used to play all Sunday afternoon she'd go to church Sunday morning, then she'd
 play cards all Sunday afternoon - with people, she'd have people down there. And so of course she got rid of this money like that. And she got so that she couldn't afford to keep it up. So of course she had to give - had to tell the lawyer that - she'd b
e having to sell the estate, and we should all have to - look for something. And of course - there was no homes to be got then. We walked miles, her and I did on a Sunday to try to find a home but we couldn't get one, couldn't find a home nowhere.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 What year would this be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
No. So - at the very last thing - my - husband's brother - offered to let us have their house, and - run it and I - there were only the two boys, because his wife had died previously. Up in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} with cancer. And so he'd got nob
ody to look after him so he said, if you like to come you can have the house and run it, and do what you like. And - I had to work for him though, I had to make all his jams and pickles.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Where was this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 That was at - Lower - you wouldn't know - 
lower End. That was - that only about - across one field from the lodge. Into Lower End. That's and - of Wavendon. It's a - it's about a mile from Wavendon but it's - belongs to it, and it's like a little - well it's like a little village now because they
've got the council houses up there. It's a real little - nice little place. Well anyway, I went - and I stayed eight months.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 What did your husband do for work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Oh he still kept on with - he got another job, gamekeeper with - a Colonel. He lived
 at Walton. Colonel did, but - we got - he had a lot of - grand - you know all round everywhere. And he kept on with that. And then - I was - went to - there, eight months and then I went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Salford{\*\xmlclose}
. Oh no I didn't. I went to Crownfield, let me tell you ri
ght, I would - I went from - Colonel - told me if I was ready by nine o'clock he'd take my bed, never mind about anything else, I could do what I liked about them, but he'd get my beds up there. So I had to be ready - and have two of me - me two beds read
y to go up to Cranfield, we got a - it was a lovely home, really I was always sorry to leave it, but it was too big for me. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Was it a house belonging to the Colonel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 He's Colonel - Earl - Colonel Earl.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Was it his house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Oh - no, he
 rented it for us. He rented it. But it was - built for a family with - and men with fourteen children. So you know it was - but it was built in just like a church. All the fireplaces were stone and there was stone right up, there was no bricks. They were
 
all stone weren't they everywhere. And the doors was all arches. It was a beautiful home though. And - well we stayed there three years. Well then the Colonel come up one day and he said, I think, he said, I've got you another home. Oh, I said, that would
 
be nice. Where is it? He said, well I want you to come down and look at it. And of course it - they had plenty of cars they had there. And he said - come outside, come on, don't wait, he said, let's go. And when I got down to Selford we couldn't find the 
-
 we couldn't find the key, who'd got the key, we didn't know - who had got it. And I went next door, no, they hadn't got it. Try Gordon. So I said - went down so - she said, do you know where Gordon - who this Gordon is, do you know where he lives? I said
,
 oh I know where he lives. So we went No. We haven't got it. Well, I said, where is it then? We don't know. Anyway - eventually Gordon come home, he soon found out where it was. And we were able to get in and look at it and it was a - we'd got a back kitc
h
en and two - like a scullery. And it could have been made into - it is now, made into a nice bathroom. And then there's a front room and there was as much - room in the front hall to have made another room, and we got three bedrooms. Oh, and I said, that'
s all right as long as I've got the three bedrooms we'll see what we can do. We went - and I stayed there twenty - twenty-three years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 What year did you go there? Do you remember?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Now - what - that's what I'm trying to think, how old you were wh
en we left the lodge. It was - it was when the war was over and we were celebrating - just before we left the lodge. The first world war. Then we went as I say, I went to Lower End, and kept house for him, for Tom, eight months.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 In the first world war did your husband go to the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Yes, he was gone three years. Yes. We were - I was left - she - no, you was - you was three - no, five when he went. Five when he went. And ten when he come home I think, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 How did you manage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 I couldn't
 tell you. We had - we - we very often had one little tiny chop - about like that, and then I used to have that and cook it and send it on to him, that's all the meat we had. Oh we - well I was in a lonely place. And we were having the - Germans that had 
b
een - they tried to get out you know, 'cos they were put - in - Grogen. They had no end of them there you see, German - prisoners. And they were escaping. And my - place was only on one floor, it was a bungalow. YES. My - my - my husband, he put a - not a
 
pistol - revolver, on the dressing table - no, there weren't, he put it on the drawers, and he said, if anyone looks in that window or comes near here, shoot. And I would have done too. Yes, 'course I would. Now. Wouldn't you? Yes. And you know, I never h
ad to shoot, I never had to and that was left there and it was left like that until he come home and finish.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Do you remember him coming home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 I should think I do. He was in - he was in that rebellion - when 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Ireland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} was in as bad as ever it is now. He had to stand three days in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
country-region}}Ireland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 in the middle of the road with his gun and he never had a crumb or a drink. He daren't leave it. He said, they were - they were really - terrible, well - we wouldn't believe what he told us when he come home - when h
e come home. But we can - I can believe it now. He said, they'd walk along with you and they'd treat you, and the next minute they'd turn round and stab you in the back. And he said, they do such dirty tricks on you. Oh he - he - he didn't like it at all.
 
He was in - Ireland a good bit, he went - he was in Fermanagh - Fermanagh, and he was up the - on the Carrow, and he was in - where - I saw where he - he was in - the other day, where these were badly fighting. And I thought, well thank goodness he isn't 
there to fight with them this time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Did he write letters to you from the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Did I work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Did he write to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Write? Oh yes. As often - as often as he could. And - and he'd come home when he could. Yes. Oh he'd come home from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Ireland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} 
- several times. He was a - he got in with a - one of the officers and he was his batman, and he had a very good job. I didn't - I didn't know him when he was coming down the drive, a man - he was doing some work for us, he'd been out with the dogs and th
at, and - they said - here's Alf coming. That was his name you see. And I looked up the drive, oh I said that isn't him. He'd got - oh he'd filled out and he was - oh he - he'd been in officer's mess.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Can you remember when you were very little?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Yes, I can remember from being three. Yes. Well I went to school you see at three.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 What sort of games did you play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
What sort of games? Well I mean we played rosa - ringa-rosy and - all that sort of thing in the playground. We had no - games lik
e they've got today. We had to make our games. But - of course we'd always have a skipping rope and a hoop, and all that, oh yes, and a top. We always had those sort of things. And then we used to play buttons, and marbles. And we used to exchange for - b
u
ttons we used to get some lovely big bright buttons, oh we used to - and then - they - they might make a necklace of them. Yes, we had some good fun out of - buttons. My mother used to say, we never know the - where to find a button in our workbox now. Wh
e
re these kids - well they didn't use that word they always used to - said children, they never used that word. My mother couldn't bear that word, she used to say, I don't like that word kids at all. No. I like to hear my children spoken of as children. Bo
th mother and father were very particular.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Were they particular about eating, the way you ate your food?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Oh - oh now, we had to sit at the table. And if we wanted to leave the table my father would say - you knew you wanted that so and so, why di
dn't you do that before, now sit where you are until you've finished, then you can go. My father carved all the meat you know, my mother never did. You know, mother do now. What little they can get. Oh - we were - we were always very well fed, but - somet
i
mes very poor. You know, the food sometimes was like it to today. Not always so good. But we were brought up mostly on boiled meat, wheat. Boiled wheat and it was called flumaty. Yes, you - I - I - I've read about it not long ago. And it was some - it's a
 
wonderful food for children or old - grown ups or anyone. We used to - when we got the new wheat in - I had to go gleaning mind you, to get the wheat. And the - and very hard work it is. Getting in that stubble. And - it's made with the wheat, when you ge
t
 the new wheat we used to wash it and - and boil it and keep boiling it, have to boil it for hours. And then - pour milk in with it, little sugar, and some raisins. And that used to make a beautiful meal. And then we had wooden - bowls and trenchers, we d
i
dn't have - for it - we never had plates like these. And they had to be scrubbed - every Saturday morning - there was trenchers' and those bowls had to be - and they was as white as - not like that but a - a - real good - yes. And oh my sisters tanned me 
m
any a time - 'cos I - I couldn't scrub like she could. She could scrub, you know, she was a grown up girl like. Well she was twelve when I was born. And the doctor said to her - when he come downstairs - he said, aren't - you pleased you've got a sister? 
S
he said, I shall be have been more pleased if it had been none. Oh dear. She knew she'd got to do something for me. And so you see that brings - her birthday - three days before mine and my brothers and my mothers. Yes. My mother was - then my brother Har
ry, he was the next one to her and then she had me again then on her birthday.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 What was your birthday like when you were little?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
We didn't have much of a birthday. The first real good birthday that I can remember is when I was thirteen. And I had two girls - come over from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Bedford{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, we didn't know they were coming. Mother had made me a little cake. And I'd got the day off you see from Shorts. And these two girls was - Florrie - Florrie Stratton, there used to be some Stratton's down here. And they
're some of the relations. And - Bessie Jephs. That was two of my girlfriends in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Bedford{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. And - we had a - real good holiday, we went haymaking over the river. In a - we could pull one another over the river with a boat you know. In the bottom of the garde
ns. We'd get into Burnham like that. And then - we went haymaking and we come and had - back and had tea and then mother said, what are you going to do now? And - I don't know, we went - had some games somewhere. And - I always remember it, Mr Hallis, he 
come along, and he was going home - and we said, give us a ride will you? I'll give you a ride, he said, to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Bedford{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, but I won't take you in the town, he said, you'll have to get down at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Union Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. So - I went with them, and they all - they went home lik
e that. And we got down at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Union Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, well then I'd got to walk back home 'cos they was home. I always remember my thirteenth birthday. Yes. I }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5979360\charrsid10883825 often}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825  wished I could get in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5979360\charrsid10883825 touch}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825  with the Strattons but I haven't been able to since I've seen their name here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 What was Christmas like when you were little?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Oh we had a very good Christmas. We always used to get a pound of cake from the church school. Lovely cake. You know my mother said sometimes when we've all gone home with it, oh you had - we had 
it according to our ages. My brothers got pound and a half, I got a pound. And - my sister - she used to get about - half a pound you see when she was going. So - she used to say, I didn't make any cake at Christmas because we have - they bring all the ca
k
e home. It - it was a - school mistress left a charity - for the - Sunday school - children, if they attended so many times. If you attended - three - you got three tickets in the morning, and three in the afternoon, if you attended. You know - morning an
d
 afternoon. But you only got a certain amount if you didn't attend these class. It was - it was left fair, very fair. And then we always used to have a big concert. Yes. Have it - you know the Howards, you've heard of the Howards, you wouldn't - well not 
n
ow because they're all gone, they're all - they're all dead now - but that house that stands in - the market place at Bedford, he's one of them. He was Mr Howard's brother, they were very good to the Parish. They used to - at Christmas specially. They use
d
 to come round - and if where they knew there was any poverty at all - they would help. Yes. Really very good. Well - one Christmas I remember particularly, my - grandmother died, eighty-four. She was eighty-four and she died in May eighty-four. Well then
 
- we went on - getting over her - her - her death like and - had - you know, making the house different and all that, and then my sister Lily was taken ill you see. Well with - German measles. And then my father was taken ill, and he had to go into hospit
a
l, well we lost me sister you see. And my father was in hospital until February. And my three brothers were all out of work. That was - that was the worst Christmas I ever knew. And the worst one I ever want to see. It really was a very hard Christmas. An
d
 - I remember - going to the hospital and me - with mother - to see father, because - his jaw - it was his jaw, they took all his teeth out this side. In this - in the - daytime, he fell off a haycart. And they thought he'd broke his neck. But they put hi
m
 in a cartwheel, and put the cartwheel back like that and it put his neck in place. But it come out you see - it come out in his - in his face. But he got over it, oh yes, he got over it all right. Tell you, we were - were a strong family. Well that was m
y
 - that was the worst Christmas I ever knew. And my mother said to me when we got to - bottom of the Bt - it was called Beckford Infirmary then, it wasn't a hospital - it wasn't the hospital, she said, I've only got sixpence. But, she said, you and get yo
ur father a quarter of a pound of butter and a quarter of a pound of sugar. 'Cos they - we had to find that. They - they weren't found. You had to find all your utensils, knife and fork and all that sort of thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 In the hospital?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Yes, that was 
in old days you know when you had to do - find everything, towels and soap and everything. And - when we come out I know she said, we can't have a bun, because, she said, we haven't got - I haven't got enough - pay for a bun. And when we got home - I'll a
lways remember that, my eldest brother said to mother as soon as she got inside the door, we've had Cannon here, and I don't think father'll ever get better. I can remember it as well as anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Had Cannon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Yes, and - and - mother said, well yo
u needn't greet us with that news because we've been and we know all about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Who was Cannon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
That was our minister. Yes. He was Canon Adam. Oh he was - he was a good man. He was a good man. And - us children knew very well - that we daren't do
 anything like they do today. He always had an umbrella with a - a knob on, and if he saw us moving, doing anything - he - he - much as to say, next time you come to school you'll get that. We daren't do anything wrong. No, well that was my - that was my 
two birthdays I can remember so well.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Did you ever go away for a holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Oh I used to go to my aunt's at Bidlam. I used to go there quite a long time. Yes. Oh yes, they - they - well they were very good to us, my uncle and aunt there, they had 
no family. They'd got no family and - they used to like to have some of us - some of us over there you know. They'd have me and - my brother Harry, they'd have - but they would never have Frank. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Why?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 I don't know, I suppose they didn't want 
him, didn't like him or something, I don't know. My - brother George used to go over - a lot on Sunday, spend Sundays there. It's a big place now, Biddenham. Yes, very - very nice place. And they - they were living under Howards they were. We used to live
 
under people you know, those days. We - we were - I don't know, we - you were glad to go to - be under somebody to feel you got somebody to cover you. You know, I couldn't tell you what - during the younger days - of what poverty there was really, there w
as really a terrible lot of poverty in villages. If there wasn't -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Were there very poor people in your village?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Yes, there were some very poor people, yes there were. They were -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 How did they live?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Well - they were glad enough to go to
 the soup kitchen. And fetch soup. They used to give out soup - three days a week to the poor. If they were very poor. And - they'd take a vessel - and they'd fill it for them, with good soup. I never - I never had to go. But - my brother - my husband sai
d
 when they were young - they've had to go. At Wavendon. But of course my home at Flatton, we were nearer the town. But otherwise I mean - I - I wouldn't want to live the life over again, not those young days. They were really - my - we used to have to hav
e
 one pair of shoes - and that used to have to last us twelve months. And you had to wear them - well - well you might say day and night almost. The - the shoemaker - and he used to do that for families. And if you paid a shilling - you paid a shilling eac
h
 for the family and he'd keep you in - shoe - in footwear. But when you've got a big family that was a big thing to find you know. My father was only getting twelve shillings a week when he'd got two children. It were only ten shillings when he were marri
ed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Did your mother and father get on well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Was it a happy home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Oh very - yes. He'd do any mortal thing for my mother, if he was ever so tired - and she wanted anything from Bedrod, he'd say - give me the money I'll go. 'Cos he never reckoned to carry any }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5979360\charrsid10883825 money}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
 about with him. He didn't like - no. Well - they didn't wear clothes, they wore sacks. They didn't wear clothes like they wear today. They slapped well - slop - I mean - they were - smock - smocked - yes, smocked here. O
h I - I used to like them. And my father went to church in a - top hat and - grey - greay - trousers. My teeth are getting a bit - worried. Yes. Sort of - they wore leggings with them. They were fustion - they called fustion britches, and then there was a
 - sort of legging went with them you see. Well he - he used to go to church in them and a top hat.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Was he good looking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Show her Frank - if you - Frank's father. Now I'll show you my brother, youngest brother - photograph, and he's exactly like my father. I looked at him yesterday and I thought, oh, if only you was alive.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Can you tell me about your wedding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Oh well, wedding. Well - we were - when I'd been home that six weeks with my mother, my mother had got so much better - she began
 to get better you see, I began to prepare - for me wedding. So - of course - it was unfortunate - he - hew was at Wavendon and I was at Flatton. Well, he'd got to come by train. He'd got to - first of all he'd got to go - walk to - Ridgmont, and then - c
a
tch a train there for Bedford, and then he'd got - four miles to walk from the old station to me. And he couldn't get away very often because - he had to get his brother to come over and - and do - whatch out for him while he was away during the day. So w
e
 had - used to get a few minutes together, that's all we used to get. He used to come and - and we - I - I got along all right, then I went up to Wavendon, and then I went to sleep at the house where I'd be living, I went there and had my furniture, said,
 oh, they said, oh - you come up, you'll - be all right. And I said, what about sleeping? And they said, well you can sleep with Julia. She'll make room for you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Was she a maid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Yes, she was - she was the parlourmaid - she was with me -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 That was the big one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Yes. Yes. And - she said, all - all right, so - anyway it was - oh a dreadful day when I - it hailed and it }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5979360\charrsid10883825 rained}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825  and it snowed and - and then blow, enough to blow your head off. It was a terrible day. And - the day we were married
, on the thirteenth of April 1903 - no - yes, 1903. Well we had a very nice wedding but it was a bit awkward when we arrived at church. Very awkward it was. But - the clerk of the church, he happened to be an old school pal of my brother's, and so he put 
us right. There - there was no clergyman when we got there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 You say there was no clergyman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
No clergyman. So - he come up - and we were standing there at the foot of the Chance and he said - well I don't know what's happened, he hadn't turned up
. He said, I'll get the - one of the boys he'd got there, I don't know - I didn't know the boy then, he said, I'll get him to run over and see what's happened. And he'd gone for his lunch and he'd forgotten all about - he was there very quickly, and he so
o
n got things put right. And - then of course there was the fuss of getting us all back up with the cars up to home. Well we couldn't afford a lot of cars. We couldn't - we had - nobody had any car then, you see, had to have either horse and trap or - what
 
you - pony trap what you could get, but anyway - we luckily - my sister knew somebody in Bedford and she got a car. Well - it was a cab, they called 'em cabbies didn't they. Well, we had this one cab and he had to go - take - father, my father and my sist
e
r and her husband first. And the two bridesmaids, I had - they wore blue, they both wore blue and - blue hats with pink. They used to say it was a very pretty wedding. But we were very disappointed in the - my cousin - she wanted him so to be a best man, 
a
nd we didn't have - we'd never seen him, we didn't know what he was like or anything, we kept saying, what's Mr Smith like? And - she - oh he's all right. So I said, well we don't want him 'cos - Joss Russ was - oh - oh - well he was in the Grenadier Guar
d
s so you know how - he was - one of the best men. He - my - Alf's best man you see. Well - this - well he come on the Saturday night, and - when he come I shall - my mother - to me - she went like this, we went in - we were in the kitchen then, we went in
to the front room and she said - did you ever see anybody like him? And I said, oh what shall we do? I said, I don't know, send him home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 What was wrong with him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
He - he - he come from the real out of the country - if ever you could find. He com
e from Bugden. And I said, well send him back to Bugden. And do you know, I can remember burying my head in my - mother's skirt, as if it was today. And - we tried to get rid of him in every way but do you think he would, no, he was foremost in everything
. And my father - said - where did you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5979360\charrsid10883825 pick him}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
 up, to - to my cousin. And she said, oh isn't he all right then? He said, well if he's right, he said, I'm all wrong. Oh we had some fun out of him. And - well I don't know - wherever she picked him up I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Did you have a honeymoon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
No, we had - only one day, that's all we had, I went straight to the lodge, Tuesday night. I slept at a - a friend of mine. My sister-in-law, she was - oh she was a beggar for doing - things like that. She got a 
bell - she borrowed a bell from the - grocers, and she tied that under the bed that she thought I was going to sleep. And she put a brush in the bed, she put all sorts of things in the bed you know, but - she didn't know we weren't going to be there. And 
o
f course she had to go home and look after her children 'cos she'd got the six children. And - we only had the one with us, Charlie was stopping with us. And - we went off and - of course when she'd cleared off - mother said, you get away now, now's your 
b
est chance. Mrs Hewlett, she was a - lived at the top house and she'd got a bedroom to spare, and she said - you can have that bedroom, the spare room, willingly, if you don't make a noise when you come in. But she said - you know what Alf is, that was he
r
 Alf, she said, if you make a noise and wake him up, she said, there'll be all gooseberries to pay. So we had to go in very quietly and while we was up - and she come in and she said, shall I put the light out. She said, he's all right, he's fast asleep. 
H
e'd been drinking you see. And she knew if he woke up what a - scene he'd cause. Well we got we had a very good - night and - when I got up the next morning - I got up to see who who was going to have breakfast and who wasn't because we were all there you
 
see for breakfast and I didn't know how mother might be. 'Cos my sister and her husband and daughter, they were staying the night as well. And I remember - my sister and I, we never - we never got on together, I don't know why it was but - she was just as
 
black as I was fair - weren't she? She was so dark. She was very very dark. Dark eyes and dark - she's the only one in the family who was dark. But anyway you - when; when - JoeRouss and all of us went back - we went back to Wavendon on - Tuesday night an
d
 we went straight to the lodge and while we were lighting a fire and trying to get a fire and I went up Lower End to this Lower End to get the bread, 'cos this sister was going to take the bread for us. Somebody stole our front door key. Luckily we'd got 
a
nother - he'd got another one. I never - we never did know who - who did - did it, but it was was somebody that knew that that key was - in that door like that. We had a - we had a - judge who it was but we never did find - we never troubled to find out. 
So long as - so I had a chain put on the door, you know the chain that - that goes along, well I had one of them put on the door. I said, well if they'll have the key they can't get in now even with a key. I said, I'm doing them that way.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Can you tell
 me about when your baby was born? What it was like having a baby then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
When I - with the first one I was really worried being on me own and being alone and being the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5979360\charrsid10883825 first one}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 . It was a bit awkward. I had to have a nurse in the house for a month. Yes. She was Irish. And - I had to - my - Mrs Yarborough, she wouldn't allow me to be }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5979360\charrsid10883825 there}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
 alone, she said, I'm - she was President of the Nursing Association, and she said, I'll demand that you have a nurse in the house before time. I will not have you lef
t down there by yourself. And she was getting married she was - when she left me that was her last job. YES. And - she was very nice and she was very good but - I didn't care about - when I saw her I - you know, I thought - oh, what is she here for. And s
h
e - she was all right, I was - I was glad really I suppose to have her. But I didn't feel I wanted her in the house somehow. But anyway - I got along all right and - I tell you I was taken - in labour - on - six o'clock on Monday night and I didn't have t
h
e boy until five o'clock Thursday morning. And then I had - had to get him - he said, it's no good, she's worn out. I'd worn myself out you see, with the pain. He said, we'll have to get her - I can remember him saying - push her head in that pillow, then
 I heard a clink, oh I thought - steel, I knew very well then what I'd got to through you see. However I got through and I was all right. But however they hurt - they hurt the boy. He - his head here. I think it was the - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5979360\charrsid10883825 tweezers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825  got too - you know, too ho
t or something. He never was right, the month he lived. And then he had convulsions. And of course they didn't - Mrs Akcoyd, she was there at the house then, she wanted to take him up to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} - to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Great Ormond Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And then Mrs Yarborough said, well I
'll take him. Then I said, well none of you will take him because I don't think for a minute he'll need it. And he didn't. I'm very glad - I was always glad he didn't - I didn't take him you see. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 How many years before this one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Well I wai
ted six years. And of course I knew then - well then I had another Irish nurse in then. She come from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Galloway{\*\xmlclose}
. Where they're doing a lot - I don't think - I don't know - that's over the border that is isn't it? Yes. Well - she didn't come in 'til Monday n
ight. She came in Monday evening - and on Tuesday morning when I had to show. Well I knew what that meant. So she said, well now - keep on - we'll keep on all day, and I said, well I've got to go and get some butter - from the next farm, we had our butter
 from the next farm. So she said, well you can go, I'll come with you. I said, I daren't go up there. She said, you'll be all right. We went up the field way, we didn't go along the road. We went up the field and we got me }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5979360\charrsid10883825 butter}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825  and we come back and I was 
all right. And the - went on 'til teatime, and pains began to get a bit worse you know, and then they began to get worse still and she said, you'd better get in the bedroom. And get - she said - get near the bed - edge of the bed. Well do you know I began
 
to be so sick and then I wanted to be - and she said, it's lovely. Oh you're doing well, I can hear her say - you're doing grand. Oh, I said, I wish it was you. I was in - in that one and under that one. She said, come on, get on the bed quick. And I got 
o
n the bed and it was here before - and she called - him, he was in the next room, she called him and she said, Mr Claridge, you'd better get up and get for the doctor quick. And - of course, he - everything went wrong when - I mean, in a hurry. He - he ha
d
n't got out - well he hadn't got across the park before she was here. And he went on to the - he didn't know of course, he went on to the doctor's, and the doctor, when he come down, he said, who is it? And he told him. So he says, well I know here, he sa
i
d, I'm going to wait and have a cup of tea before I come, he said. But, he said, I know what she is. Anyway he never hurried himself. Didn't matter. She was all right you know, nurse was good you see, she could deliver - and when he come he - I shall alwa
y
s remember how he come in laughing and he - looked at me as I lay in the bed. And I said, yes, I said, you ought to look at me, I said, she should have the money, not you. He said - who's garters are they up there? I said, they're mine, he said - well you
'
ll want some new ones when you get up. I can tell you that. And with that he sat - had a chair and sat down and - did what there was to be done. And had a cup of tea of course as usual, and he went off, he never troubled any more about me. And of course s
h
e stayed and - we had her there. Now - I hardly - hardly knew we - oh she was very ill. To be - yes, she was very ill. Now what did you have? You couldn't get any milk. I - I hadn't got any milk, I hadn't got sufficient to feed her. It went off you see. I
 
- I was having to run about, I was having to work pretty hard then. And I think that was a lot to do with it you see. And - and my milk left me and I was in terrible - way to know what to do and what to get. And I went to my doctor - what we call - old do
c
tor. And I said, what can I do, we tried all foods we could, Allenbury's and - all the foods like that, nothing seemed to suit her. So - he - the milk that we got from the milkman didn't seem to - as if it have enough in it to strengthen her, to - you kno
w, to make her sort of grown. She seemed at a standstill. Well - the - place where we lived, they kept \{ILLEGIBLE\}
 cows, so he suggested to me that I write to the lady, she was - they was in London for the season, in Brooke Street, I can always remember the
y was in Brooke Street. And I don't know what it's like now but used to be a very nice place then. Well - I wrote to her and I told her condition she was in, we couldn't get anything to suit her, and Doctor Holmes had suggested that I write and asks her i
f
 I could have a pint of milk - straight from the olderly cow every day for a little while to see if it would settle - set her, you know, going. And she wrote back at once and said, yes, get - she called him Claridge you see - get Claridge to take a can or
 
a jug up to the house and when the milk comes in every morning ask the housekeeper to put a pint aside, no matter what she was doing or what anybody was doing, the cowman or anyone, they were to put that pint of milk aside. Well he used to manage to call 
f
or it about - just about half past eight, and used to bring it home and I used to make a quart of barley water, Robinson's barley water, and I used to pour this - barley water straight onto the milk, you see, and that scalded it and then I took it to the 
i
ce house, we had an ice house in our yard, and I used to take it straight to the ice house and put it there and fetch it - what I wanted out every feed. Well that set her going, then of course I always thing that that's what's given her - well - she's alw
ays had good health - since. She wasn't really - ill but she wouldn't - she didn't }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5979360\charrsid10883825 seem}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825  to make any headway, she couldn't - we couldn't get her on anyway. And from that I never had any more trouble with her. And she gave her that til she was three years old
. That milk, yes. That - that was milk - used to be cream you know, that milk, yes. And - then -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Did you know much about babies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
No, I'd been away from home I - I hadn't any - anything to do with them you see, I knew I needed a - when - I was i
n a hospital - fourteen weeks and I had to look after a baby there, they were so short of staff that we had to take - I was - twenty- I was twenty-four I think - or twenty-five, something like that. Between - between that - twenty-four and twenty-five, an
d
 I had to take - we all had - people my age - girls my age, had to take a baby, and we had to have them day and night. And I learnt a good bit, and do you know - when that - person, the mother of that baby come to fetch it away he didn't want to go, he wa
n
ted to stop with me you see. Well it wasn't a baby, he was about a year and eight months old, something like that. But he was a - a child, so I had a good bit do - feed him you see. But that's all I ever had, I never had anything to do with anything, I wa
s always in the cooking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Did you have a neighbour to help you, who did you ask if you wanted to know something?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 I had no neighbour.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Your mother wasn't near was she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 No, was nowhere near. I wonder if I - I've got the photograph of - of
 the lodge. I believe it's just on the top of my drawers but - it's underneath that - blue blouse. Oh - don't - that's not going in there. And then - anyway she was an elderly woman. But she's about eighty odd, and she lived in a little farm right up the 
h
ill, I had to go right up a hill. And - she couldn't give me much advice, she'd only had one boy. And - he'd been on - he was born on the farm you know and he was a big - oh, that sort of type. She was a dear old soul, she - used to say, I wish I knew mor
e about children so that I could tell you. But - she grew up to know how you grew up didn't she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Did your husband help with the baby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Oh - yes, when - well he had to help, but he couldn't help very much because - his work took him out so much. Yo
u see - and he couldn't very well be indoors, otherwise something'd go wrong outside. So - I never bothered him if I could help it. But - I had to - I had - had a good - a very good sister-in-law. Yes. And - she lived - about - well what shall I say - ten
 
minutes walk weren't it? Yes, quite ten minutes walk. And she'd got a family, nice little - and she used to help. And - when she used to come soon as she used to run in here she used to start screaming. And she'd say, I'd give it you know, I'd give you a 
good smack.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Did you ever smack her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Well I didn't have much reason. Soon as she could - get away outside at all she - I found her outside one day in the paddock between two horse's legs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 How old was she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Oh - she - she was only about a
 year and eight month - nine months. She crawled. And Simeon, that's the big grey horse, he was standing with - his two forefeet over here, and his backfeet over her like that. Oh you know when I give my - my heart come up, I thought, oh if he moved. And 
I
 daren't shout. So I had to lead her and I gradually crept up to him and talked quietly to him, 'cos he was - lovely old horse, he was put there for rest. And he'd got little pony, Shetland pony with him. And I was so afraid that would come up and kick hi
s heels up. But however, I crept up to him and I pulled her out underneath like that. And I got on with - further along with her. And that was the beginning. She was always creeping out then somewhere.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Who did she play with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 She'd nobody to play 
with, only dogs. That's all she had. The dogs. She used to - we had a lake there, we had the lake. She - she was only about two years old, she used to go fishing. Yes, used to catch more fish than the men did didn't you. She had no one to play with at all
.
 Until she went to school. And then when she went to school she got a mile and a quarter to go and they used to fight like hooligans along that road, coming along, the children did. I've - I've parted 'em many a time when they've been going along. And - w
e
ll until she was five she had no one to play with at all. No, she just had to maker her own - yes. When she did go there the children looked at her like as if she was a - big stranger. You know. She didn't want anything to do with them. Oh, you did - you 
h
ad - master Peter didn't you? The little boy at that house, at Wavendon House, he was - of course he was born - at Christmas, and he was put out on the - outdoors like they do, and the snow was on the ground and - of course he caught - I think it was asth
m
a or something, bronchitis I believe, and when he got better they used to bring him down in the pram, down the back drive. And then - she used to see him and they used to be able to - talk and play together in the pram, because nanny used to bring him dow
n
. And she used to say, well he's got no one to play with and she's got no none to play with, so they didn't mind. You see, so she had a playmate when she got a bit older. But of course - I mean, it was only at certain times and certain days. When he began
 
to get older you see - her talk and his talk didn't agree. But he'd always like - he always did like to come and see us didn't he. Yes. Nanny would bring him, she'd say, well - one day let's hope he'll have to mix up with perhaps very poor people and nobo
d
y knows what we've got - got to go through. What he's going to do, they didn't know what he'd do. It was Peter Ackroyd, there was two children born there the same day - and - mind you, not the same year, but the same - on the same day, Christmas Day and -
 
it was on the same day - came the same year on the same day. Of course there was - that family had gone then, then the next family that come in, they - they had a - that was a - American one as I told you, the three children. And then - when we had the ot
her one, they used to come - he was a big boy, he used to come down and play with her. He was too rough. He - he really was too - well, Peter. Yes, and -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Did she ever go up to the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Oh yes. And when - a daughter got - fair - eight years old
 one, she - she's the same age as her. And when she got eight years old her father had a little house out - built outside - for her to be in and have her own little place for cooking - and let her work, keep it clean. Then she used to have her up there an
d they knew how to do cooking. Then they used to have teaparties. Oh when she got older she had a better life but - it was a very young life. It was - bad for me. I'd gone - out from where I'd got a lot of people, and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Were you lonely?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 I was a -
 I was lonely a good many times, yes. But I was left night as well. You see, my husband used to be out at night and some - very often he'd come home - have a meal and go out three o'clock in the morning. I had a - I had a - well people used to say, oh I w
o
uldn't live there for the world. But I did live a good many years there. YES. But I - I got better as I got - as I got more settled down. It was when I first went and I - was so - after living with a lot of people - going there and having no one to speak 
to at all. Only myself.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Were you very strict with her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Oh yes, I had to be because - I never knew when they were coming in. Because, they used the back drive more so than they did the front drive because my drive was a better - in better conditi
on than the front. The front was - uneven and - the cattle got on it. You see the cattle were in the park. And - and then they used - and they used to be messing on it you see. Well my drive was all right, if the cattle never messed on my drive, that went
 
further along and went to the lake, what they did I don't know in there. Anyway - we had about - oh she used to - well - she used to go off in that boat. That's where she used to be most of the time when she got about four years old. I used to say, she'll
 
be drowned before she's finished, I'm sure she will. So one day she said to me, why don't you come out, she said, I'll row you. And I said, oh when I've got - when I get in the boat I said, oh let me get out. I remember that so - let me get out. I said, y
ou'll drown me. She did nearly drown her uncle. Yes. She got - she - he got in it, he said, that girl. He said, that girl can do anything. He - he said, she's nearly drowned me. I had to wash his trousers and things for him before he could go back. Yes. }
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5979360\charrsid10883825 Anyway}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
 we got through and she went to school, and I was very glad she did when she did. But you see - I had to always keep her nice because I never knew when they were coming. And I never knew who they were bringing in. And Mrs - Ackroyd told a lady that she 
brought down with her, she - they - she was one for dogs, this lady was, she used to have those - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5979360\charrsid10883825 Pomeranians}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 . And she'd always got three tagging behind her. And she used to bring these dogs down and - what you call - walks. And she'd come as far as the bi
g gate, and then she'd - perhaps come in you see, well I didn't matter what time of day it was, she'd go and fetch her out of her cot. And she'd say, I'm never afraid to fetch her out of her cot because she's kept as well as if she was in my own nursery. 
I
 can - I can - I did hear her say that to this lady and I thought, oh well, that's a feather. Yes, it was. But she was - very - she was very good to her. Yes. She'd often bring her something like - special fruit, little fruits you know, when strawberries 
was ripe, to - just - perhaps four very large ones, or a tiny - lovely place you know, and she'd say now, give her these when she wakes. But not all at once.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Was your husband strict with her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 No, he had no - well - he didn't like - babies, he lik
ed children. He liked children when they got older. And - but he didn't care - he didn't like - his - well his place was with dogs and animals. You know, all kinds of animals, everything in the line of animals. When there's - when there was any animals to
 
be shot, he always had to do it. It was never sent away. That's why Simeon was waiting for his - to be put down - but he - they didn't like to put him down, he'd been such a faithful old friend. Mr Ackroyd said he carried him many many miles and he didn't
 like to - I used to see seven of 'em go out sometimes of a morning hunting. YES. There was him and her, Mr and Mrs Ackroyd, that was two. Miss Drybath, that was three, Miss Audrey four. Peter five. Second horseman six. And then another man on a li}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5979360\charrsid10883825 ttle one - pony to relieve Pe}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
ter on his pony when he got tired. Bring him home. I - I - I had a - I had a very - very good life as regards - when I did get settled down. And then - when it come to moving - the lease was out you see. The lease went out and - Sir Hen
ry Hall, that was whom my - husband went away with when he was eleven years old. He went to Somerset - Wiltshire I mean, in - when he was eleven and - well - this Sir Henry and Mr Ackroyd, that was the one that had worked the lease out of Mr Hetherington'
s
 - Mr - you wouldn't remember him but Hetherington's in London was a big shop - big - oh tremendous store like and they had - the house, they took the lease out and his wife come down and she died the first night. So of course he let - got someone to work
 -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Tell me about the games?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
Yes. I was going to say - I wonder if you knew - that jolly miller. It's a most exciting game. And it's played now. YES? It's not very long ago that we were at a party where it was played. And it's - we - begin with -
 it won't go on there will it? Well it's - a little bit - there was a jolly miller and he lived by himself. As the wheel went round he made his wealth. One hand in the hopper and the other in the bag, as he reached it - as the wheel went round he made his
 
grab, and we had to rush to catch - the next one that is. Would you know that? Oh it's good, it - it's most exciting isn't it. Everybody gets so hot and they get so - and they get so - they get muddled up and sometimes there's - instead of being one left 
in the middle there's sometimes three and four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1705933 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 Did you play it at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2304479 MC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid686957\charrsid10883825 
We play it anywhere, it's a - it's such a good game. We used to - yes, we used to play - always play it at school when we - really good. Then - there's a jolly miller what
's it, I can't see me own writing. Oh - it really is, it's a game that - everybody loves and gets so excited. And - the drop handkerchief was a very good one. We always used to to choose a boy - for dropping the handkerchief if we could but - had always -
 
had some difficulty in doing that, we dropped the handkerchief and very often he was looking somewhere else and he didn't see it, you see, and the person that dropped it had gone. She'd got in somewhere, you know that? Oh and that - shuttlecock and battle
d
ore was our first spring - you know that? Well - you - I wish you'd bring the children in, they wouldn't - they wouldn't mind. We don't mind. Oh wouldn't it - wouldn't it - would they interfere? Well anyway, this shuttlecock, it's - piece of - buy - you c
an buy it or you can make it. It's a piece of cork about like - not big as that, about - about - a piece of cork about like that.
